<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,538,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Medium sized, robust, overall dark brown/black flies, 
<quantity box="[788,918,538,564]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="22.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="22.0">22–23 mm</quantity>
. Legs contrasting black and brown. Tergites with quadrate dark brown/black patches. This description is based on 
<specimenCount box="[989,1093,578,604]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="female">2 female</specimenCount>
specimens found in Malaise traps (see Discussion below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,538,1567]" box="[198,383,658,684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,383,658,684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Adult. Female.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,538,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,274,698,724]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Head:</emphasis>
Face covered in dense dark gold pile. Mystax hair sparse, long, gold. Genae with sparse white hair. Long, strong yellow/white peristomal (oral) bristles. Occipital fringe of long gold hair merging into black proclinate postocular bristles. Ocellar hair black; orbital hair gold; long thin gold facial hair extending over mystax. Antenna black with gold and black hair. Segments 1 &amp; 2 with black dorsal hair and yellow ventral hair. Style apex “spear-shaped” (wide medially with tapered apex). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[879,972,858,884]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Thorax</emphasis>
dark brown with long black evenly dispersed acrostical hair. Paramedian stripes dark brown, broad, merging into median stripe; lateral spots broad, well defined. Pleura gold pollinose with gold and black hair; dorsal anepisternal hair black. Chaetotaxy with: 2 notopleural, 3 supraalar, and 3–4 postalar bristles. Posterior dorsocentral hair long, black. Sparse fine gold scutellar hair, subapical gold and black bristles; long gold marginal bristles. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1044,1103,1018,1044]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Legs</emphasis>
brown, tan &amp; black. Fore &amp; mid femora with broad black anterodorsal streaks, anteroventral on hind femora, all apices black. Tibiae yellow/gold with black bristles. Tarsi yellow/gold with black bristles. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[950,1029,1098,1124]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Wings</emphasis>
similar in venation to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1849" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Promachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anicius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Promachus anicius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[254,328,1138,1164]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1766,1790]" captionTargetBox="[164,1427,182,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-72@3.[163,1428,182,1760]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Male wing. 1. Philodicus integer; 2. Promachus nigribarbatus; 3. Promachus anicius; 4. Promachus yesonicus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107789" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107789/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); veins tinged yellow/brown; cells r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[764,772,1154,1168]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">1</subScript>
&amp; r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[825,850,1154,1168]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">2+3</subScript>
darker. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[946,1068,1138,1164]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Abdomen</emphasis>
dark brown/black integument, brown pollen with gold hair; yellow/gold lateral hair, hair with twisted apices on tergites 1 &amp; 2. Tergites with quadrate dark brown/black patches. Tergites 1 &amp; 2 with lateral brown pollen only, mostly integumental brown. Tergites 3–6 medially bare with sparse yellow hair, laterally brown pollinose with yellow hair. Sternites with sparse, long trailing, yellow hair. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[771,859,1301,1327]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–35" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1669,1693]" captionTargetBox="[168,1346,181,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-102@10.[151,1436,181,1792]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 33–35. Promachus anicius. 33. male sternite 8—South Korea; 34. male sternite 8—China; 35. female genitalia, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107799" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107799/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[1002,1228,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Promachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anicius">
<emphasis box="[1002,1228,1302,1327]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Promachus anicius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1887" box="[1291,1436,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Promachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yesonicus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1436,1302,1327]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">P. yesonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,246,1341,1367]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–32" captionStartId="9.[151,269,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[168,1144,440,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-140@9.[168,1436,440,1910]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 26–32. Promachus yesonicus. 26. male genitalia, lateral; 27. female genitalia, lateral; 28. male genitalia, dorsal; 29. male genitalia, ventral; 30. gonostylus; 31. gonopod; 32. aedeagus, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107797/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
), cerci wide, plate-like.
</paragraph>
